<br>
I have done several with friends, and one pick up group. With friends, we all knew what to do, from experince, and the more dungeons we do, the better we get at them. The puller is a paladin that can pacify and single pull. Worked like a charm, we had a very good team. There was even times as the wizard, I could sit a fight out. We had a few times for med, but for the most part, it was pull a room, move in, pull the hall, pull the next room, move in. <br>
<br>
In the pick up group, no one wanted to pull, the cleric didn't want to pacify, no one worked well together. We bailed on the mission 10 minutes into it. You can't go into one of these with a time limit and spend half the time working things out.<br>
<br>
That is why pick up groups aren't that good in LDoN. Outside of LDoN, you have the lesuire of taking your time to tweek a team and find a system that works. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gravely>Gravely</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 122<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/11/03 4:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4005.topic&index=54>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.visi.com/~mlm/eq/gravely_face_60x60.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_supermad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: LDoN Level Restrictions</span><hr size=1> Pickup groups are not always evil but people tend to get burned by them enough they aren't willing to risk it.  Why?<br>
<br>
1) people in pickup groups have no sense of loyalty to each other built up by friendship.  Getting kinda tired, and the group wiped?  &quot;/gs hey guys I'm really tired, I think I'm going to hit the hay.&quot;  In a group with friends, and one is about 30-45 minutes from a ding?  &quot;/gs hey guys, lets get ____ his/her level and then I'm gonna go to sleep&quot;.  Lack of loyalty to each other results in people sometimes not willing to take the extra steps to make the group succeed, but just going to bed or leaving to find another group, etc, at the first sign of difficulty.<br>
<br>
2) Lack of confidence.  Groups work best when everyone has confidence in everyone else.  If I hesitate to aggressively heal the tank who grabs aggro on a 3 pull, because I don't have confidence in the enchanter to lock things down asap and keep them off of me, the tank dies, then we all die, and things suck.  Don't tell me everyone who comes to a pickup group has confidence in everyone else automatically, because I've seen them not demonstrate it.  For example, even if I choose to heal said tank, the tank might not choose to have confidence in me and in the enchanter, and might not do what (s)he can to step up and start taking hits.  The enchanter might not have confidence in the group not breaking mez and might root mobs on the tank instead.  I go ahead with my heal, heal again, and suddenly root breaks, and I am dead.  All sorts of bad things happen when people lack confidence in each other.  Sure, a pickup group with a chance for members to earn each other's confidence does well after a while, and those are fun pickup groups, but it's not always the case.<br>
<br>
3) Peoples' gear/skill vary greatly.  When you group with friends, you tend to have a similar equipment and skill level as they do.  Even if you don't, you know what to expect.  In a pickup group, you might be looking for a tank, choosing a level 65 person, and thinking &quot;hmm, my friends/guildmates/etc who are paladins have about 7,000 hps with cleric buffs, so I'll plan accordingly&quot;.  Then, you get to the dungeon, and your paladin starts dropping like a rock.  You land a crit heal with him/her at 33% and discover it only healed them for 2986 out of the 3800 your crit was for.  You do some quick math and your paladin tank has less than 4500 hitpoints with virtue (1405) and brells mountainous (225), so they're running under 2900 unbuffed.  You were expecting 5500+ hps.  How you react maybe says a lot about you.  If the group can handle your tank having half the unbuffed hitpoints of your rogue, but being good at giving the rogue a back to stab, and not dying because of defensive AAs or whatever, and healer mana isn't a problem, then great.  But if your tank maybe doesn't have the defensive AAs, and due to levels the mobs are nasty and hit for 9% of your tanks buffed hitpoints such that you can't even risk using Complete Heal, and you're healing twice as much as you expected, well, it can make you feel frustrated, and want to leave, or not give the group your all.  Similar things can be said about being excited to add a 65 rogue to the group only to find out he's using a slime coated harpoon and locustlure, or adding an enchanter with 583 AAs only to find out the person just picked her up on ebay 3 days ago, and she's wearing an oracle robe, has 150 intelligence, 130 charisma, and 1100 hps unbuffed.  Even the reverse works.  Suppose you're level 60ish, have run 3 only, haven't had time to work on gear too much because you're a casual player (which I support by the way!)  You're in a group, and you've managed to find 4 other people with similar gear/level/AA situations, and so far you're happy because everyone in the group meets expectations.  Now you're looking for a cleric, and you use the LFG tool, and find a 65 cleric as the only cleric lfg.  You send a tell inviting them to come do an LDoN dungeon and they say &quot;whew, I thought I'd never get a group, thanks!&quot; and comes running to join the group.  Someone notices the cleric is throwing around level 65 spells, right clicking an endless supply of items, etc, and eventually it comes up that the cleric has 492 AAs, elemental planes gear, plays 14 hours a day, has 5500 unbuffed hitpoints and 6500 unbuffed mana, etc.  You might worry they are not going to be happy with this group.  You might feel a desire to prove yourself or live up to their expectations that might sour the group (maybe you won't at all, and if not, good for you).  And, depending on this cleric's personality, it might be great or might be awful.  If they are constantly dropping hints that they're unhappy or find the group inadequate, it can wreck your fun, right?  But if they are positive, encouraging, etc, like everyone else, it can be great.  What I'm trying to say is that as a player, you may have certain expectations based on what you bring to EQ (time committment, level, gear, skill, etc.  If the group doesn't match those expectations you might be quite disappointed.  In pickup groups, you get what you get, and most people don't interview potential additions to the group extensively before inviting them.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I can totally understand people not enjoying pickup groups for reasons coming from the above.  They might view 3 positive pickup groups as insufficient to make up for 1 bad one.  They may just be unwilling to lower expecations.  Whatever, it's their choice.  Personally, I usually prefer not to do pickup groups, but will from time to time, especially if I'm feeling rather social.<br>
<br>
I think LDoN indeed makes pickup groups even more iffy because most missions have a high focus on damage output (DPS or mobs killed per session or whatever (different things... a high DPS group that doesn't keep 1 mob mezzed/rooted in camp might kill slower than a lower DPS group that never waits for a pull)).  Because you have a need to be efficient and kill quickly, and a goal to reach in a timed environment, there's going to be more pressure and higher expectations.  People need to rely on each other, and take the risk that everyone in the group will do their job.  Basically, it's going to exasperate the problems of a pickup group, at least in my opinion.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I'm not anti-pickup groups (had a fun one the first night of LDoN) but I can understand where anti-pickup group people are coming from, especially if they put a high emphasis on success.<br>
<br>
